Defendants contend:
(1) Dean Blair's TAP 33 analysis was consistent with the policy's plain language — Plaintiff is not a "Covered Party" as defined, and the instructor-student evaluative relationship during litigation is not a "Conflict of Interest" under the policy (Dkt. 34 at 6-8);
(2) Blair's silence on the August 25, 2025 email was not actionable because no fiduciary or confidential relationship existed between university administrators and Plaintiff to trigger a duty to speak (Dkt. 34 at 9, citing Sunquest Info. Sys., 40 F. Supp. 2d at 656);
(3) Plaintiff admitted in his own pleadings that he "immediately recognized" Blair's TAP 33 reading was wrong and was "no longer relying on Defendants' representations" as of July 24, 2025 — therefore no justifiable reliance (Dkt. 34 at 8-9);
(4) Plaintiff's claims are internally inconsistent — he alleges that both responding to his emails (Selcer) and not responding (Blair) constituted fraud (Dkt. 34 at 5);
(5) The consultation between Blair and Selcer produced assurances of fair treatment and offers of academic support — evidence of intent to help, not deceive (Dkt. 34 at 10);
(6) Courts should defer to academic institutions' professional judgment regarding academic decisions (Dkt. 34 at 8 n.2, citing Jain v. Carnegie Mellon Univ.).

Defendants contend:
(1) Blair's consultation with Selcer was routine academic administration — she could not respond to Plaintiff's transfer request without checking course availability and academic progress with the department chair (Dkt. 34 at 10);
(2) The consultation evidenced intent to help, not malice — it resulted in assurances of fair treatment and offers of academic support (Dkt. 34 at 10);
(3) No underlying tort exists to support the conspiracy because Blair's TAP 33 analysis was correct on the policy's plain terms (Dkt. 34 at 10);
(4) Plaintiff's characterization of coordinated institutional responses as "conspiracy" reflects his refusal to engage with well-established university processes, not evidence of unlawful agreement (Dkt. 25 at 6);
(5) Selcer's continuation as Plaintiff's instructor was not retaliatory because he held that role before and after Plaintiff's protected activity — therefore not an overt act in furtherance of conspiracy (Dkt. 34 at 10 n.3).
